      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4f6ac9f7a9139e8e",
      "text": "Solidarity with the Palestinian uprising against the military dictatorship in the territories occupied by Israel and solidarity with the protests of Israelis of Palestinian origin against their discrimination are a necessity of left-wing internationalism. However, among German left-wingers, it is taking on strange forms. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1bd070f5009e60e5",
      "text": "We have the definite suspicion that the solidarity work organized under the slogan of anti-Zionism is done less for the sake of the Palestinians than for the sake of the favourable opportunity to finally be able to live out anti-Semitic feelings and intentions under a political cover. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1f5831e96e81bc19",
      "text": "The immediate cause of this sad statement is a \"Kampfblatt für den Aufstand\" (\"Fighting paper for the uprising\") circulating in Freiburg with the title: \"Immer rebellieren\" (\"Always rebel\"). Under the headline \"The Zionist state entity 'Israel' must disappear!\", the paper spreads the bleak thesis that Zionism and fascism are essentially the same and the authors claim that Nazis and Israeli state founders worked hand in hand to expel the Palestinians. The sentence often uttered by fascists that the Jews should be grateful to Hitler is repeated here in an anti-imperialist guise. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0865954bcfee65b6",
      "text": "How do German 'leftists' come to threaten an Israeli state with annihilation? Why should Israel be the only state that should be wiped out? How does it come to a demand that no anti-imperialist has ever been heard to make in relation to Iraq and the Kurds, for example? Otherwise the outraged anti-imperialist calls for the overthrow of the government, a radical change in policy, etc. – when it comes to Israel, the only thing that should help is wiping it off the map. How so? Where does the special commitment to 'anti-Zionism' come from? "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "50b4c973fe76267b",
      "text": "We have become accustomed to hearing the so-called 'anti-imperialists' or friends of the armed struggle talk about the revolution like the blind talk about the rainbow and the deaf talk about the 'International'. We must not get used to the fact that anti-imperialist persecution mania and conspiracy psychosis are now being played out on those who narrowly escaped. We have had to get used to the fact that the anti-imperialist habitus has been patched up from trench and front-line romanticism, from chauvinism and intellectual hatred. These are the classic ideological and psychological forms of reactionary sentiment. Now they are condensed into anti-Semitism and have found their ideal object in it. We must not get used to this. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "cf466b19884c03b6",
      "text": "Until now, one could assume that it was a matter of course for the left to speak out against hatred of Jews. Until now, the battle cry \"The Jews are our misfortune\" could only be read in Nazi posters. Now the 'turn' seems to have swung to the left. But where the turned conservative becomes a rabid German nationalist, the turned leftist becomes a Stalinist and adds the slogan of 'anti-Zionism' to his arsenal of revolutionary phrases. We therefore state: "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b9bd53dbb401ce9b",
      "text": "Not everyone who acts against capital is therefore already on the left. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e60077bbc13094b1",
      "text": "The intellectual neglect of the left has led to the Marxist vocabulary being used to justify any kind of nonsense. The talk of 'anti-Zionism', which purports to be revolutionary, also thrives on this. However, one must not be fooled by the rebellious jingling of words. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "af86c5b4897efc25",
      "text": "Adolf Hitler was also against 'capital'. He too was an 'anti-capitalist' of the highest order, who always found strong words against the \"grasping capital\" that deprived the workers and laborers of the best. In \"Mein Kampf\" he acts against the decadent citizens, against the \"pepper bags\" and their \"selfish representation of interests\", against the speculators and against usury. And the embodiment of speculation was the Jew, the money-grubber par excellence, whose intellectual faction had previously deprived the people of the best and destroyed their \"national identity\" with their \"abstract\", \"bloodless\" and \"detached\" speeches. "
